 membrane fusion at the plasma membrane. In addition, SARS‐CoV‐2 can enter the cell by endocytosis and be proteolytically activated by cathepsin L, although this is not a major mode of SARS‐CoV‐2 infection. SARS‐CoV‐2 variants with enhanced infectivity have been emerging throughout the ongoing pandemic, and there is a close relationship between enhanced infectivity and changes in S protein cleavability. All four variants of concern carry the D614G mutation, which indirectly enhances S1/S2 cleavability by furin. The P681R mutation of the delta variant directly increases S1/S2 cleavability, enhancing membrane fusion and SARS‐CoV‐2 virulence. Changes in S protein cleavability can significantly impact viral infectivity, tissue tropism, and virulence. Understanding these mechanisms is critical to counteracting the coronavirus pandemic.","publicationTypes":["Review","JournalArticle"],"tldr":{"model":"tldr@v2.0.0","text":"In this review, this process is discussed, with particular focus on the novel coronav virus, severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS‐CoV‐2), and there is a close relationship between enhanced infectivity and changes in S protein cleavability."}},"tag":"EXP"},{"id":3481,"details":{"paperId":"4290b4ec7178af8b5cda5a832e184c29a37dad82","externalIds":{"PubMedCentral":"7454804","MAG":"3042158485","DOI":"10.1093/jmcb/mjaa033","CorpusId":"220436746","PubMed":"32642770"},"title":"Proteome-wide data analysis reveals tissue-specific network associated with SARS-CoV-2 infection","abstract":"Abstract For patients with COVID-19 caused by severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2), the damages to multiple organs have been clinically observed. Since most of current investigations for virus–host interaction are based on cell level, there is an urgent demand to probe tissue-specific features associated with SARS-CoV-2 infection. Based on collected proteomic datasets from human lung, colon, kidney, liver, and heart, we constructed a virus-rec