RAAS modulation in the setting of SARS-CoV-2 remain limited. Conclusion Proposed interventions for SARS-CoV-2 predominantly focus on viral microbiology and aim to inhibit viral cellular injury. While these therapies are promising, immediate use may not be feasible, and the time window of their efficacy remains a major unanswered question. An alternative approach is the modulation of the specific downstream pathophysiological effects caused by the virus that lead to morbidity and mortality. We propose a preponderance of evidence that supports clinical equipoise regarding the efficacy of RAAS-based interventions, and the imminent need for a multisite randomised controlled clinical trial to evaluate the inhibition of the RAAS–SCoV axis on acute lung injury in COVID-19. The interplay of SARS-CoV-2 with the renin–angiotensin–aldosterone system probably accounts for much of its unique pathology. Appreciating the degree and mechanism of this interaction highlights potential therapeutic options, including blockade (ARBs). https://bit.ly/3aue4tS","publicationTypes":["JournalArticle","Review"],"tldr":{"model":"tldr@v2.0.0","text":"A preponderance of evidence is proposed that supports clinical equipoise regarding the efficacy of RAAS-based interventions, and the imminent need for a multisite randomised controlled clinical trial to evaluate the inhibition of the RAAS–SCoV axis on acute lung injury in COVID-19 is proposed."}},"tag":"EXP"},{"id":1241,"details":{"paperId":"f13b9ec7852b4153d6bfae053ee1a016687d6da6","externalIds":{"PubMedCentral":"7428439","MAG":"3048894313","DOI":"10.1016/j.gene.2020.145057","CorpusId":"221117927","PubMed":"32805314"},"title":"Unravelling host-pathogen interactions: ceRNA network in SARS-CoV-2 infection (COVID-19)","abstract":null,"publicationTypes":["JournalArticle"],"tldr":{"model":"tldr@v2.0.0","text":"This integrative analysis has identified noncoding RNAs and their plausible targets, which could effectively enhance the understanding of molecul